page.title: We Need a Global Standard for Reporting Cyber Attacks
page.author: Marc BarrachinAlgirde Pipikaite
page.excerpt: Regulators should be collecting a standardized data set, so we can measure the threat.

cmtlist.0x3c553163bd5feb8770eac6b6963a51eb2c5054: Looking ahead, one happy possibility from the rise of AI is that people’s ability to understand one another and work together may become more valued as technological tools overtake us in other areas.

To do this, we must agree on a standard taxonomy of cyber events so that we can track and understand the consequences of any attack. This taxonomy should include:

    dates relevant to the incident (when it occurred, when it was initially detected, when it was reported)
    type of incident (breach, malware, distributed denial of service [DDoS], etc.)
    size of impact on financial results or ability to conduct business
    type of impact (data breach, financial loss, operational, legal, reputational, intellectual property, etc.)
    method used to access the network or data (phishing, ransomware, virus, zero days exploitation, etc.)
    how the incident was resolved (patch, update firewall configuration or software, etc.) and cost of the resolution
